We managed to train a major new foundation model at a University, but (unlike LLMs) also had to run it over every 10-metre pixel of the Earth's land surface for every year from 2017 to 2025. This is because the TESSERA geospatial mode supports ready-to-use "map tiles" that make using it for mapping as easy as possible. This post describes how we did the first major run, first training with the [AMD Accelerator Cloud](https://aac.amd.com/), and then later inferring on [Vultr](https://vultr.com)'s bare-metal AMD MI325X infrastructure that they kindly gave us early access to.

## Training TESSERA v1

TESSERA is [trained](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.20380) using a modified [Barlow Twins](https://arxiv.org/abs/2103.03230) self-supervised learning objective. The model has parallel Transformer-based encoders  (one for [Sentinel-2 optical](https://dataspace.copernicus.eu/data-collections/copernicus-sentinel-missions/sentinel-2) data and one for [Sentinel-1 radar](https://sentinels.copernicus.eu/copernicus/sentinel-1)) whose outputs are fused by a [multilayer perceptron](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multilayer_perceptron) into a single 128-dimensional embedding per 10m2 pixel. The full model has around 1.4 billion parameters, though the vast majority are in the projector network that is discarded after training. This leaves the encoder itself as a lean 46 million parameters; pretty small for a learnt observational model of the Earth's land!

### Visualising the pipeline

The training dataset is where we get into serious systems scale. We build up a matrix of images for every 10m2 that form a cross-seasonal view of that particular point, called a "d-pixel".
Here's what a few of these d-pixel tiles look like as they move through the system:

