The training pipeline comprises roughly 800 million d-pixels drawn from 3000 globally distributed [MGRS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_Grid_Reference_System) tiles, downsampled 400:1 from the full Sentinel archive. The self-supervised trick is that we randomly sample cloud-free subsets of each d-pixel's time series and train the model to produce the same embedding regardless of which subset it sees. This forces the model to learn representations that are invariant to cloud cover and temporal gaps, which overcome the biggest hassle when processing satellite data 'manually'.

Last summer, AMD gave us early access to the **AMD Accelerator Cloud** to train the model. We trained for a single epoch on 16 AMD Instinct MI300X GPUs (192 GB HBM3 each), consuming approximately 6,200 GPU hours. The stack was PyTorch with [Fully Sharded Data Parallel](https://docs.pytorch.org/tutorials/intermediate/FSDP_tutorial.html) and [Automatic Mixed Precision](https://docs.pytorch.org/tutorials/recipes/recipes/amp_recipe.html), running on [ROCm](https://www.amd.com/en/products/software/rocm.html). We used a per-GPU batch size of 2k d-pixels and a global batch size of 32k with a custom data shuffling pipeline to ensure each mini-batch contained d-pixels from diverse geographic locations and acquisition conditions. This remixing was critical for preventing the model from overfitting to regional characteristics and let us train a global foundation model for anywhere on the planet.

### Crop clustering in embedding space

One way to see the power of TESSERA's learned representations is to visualise how the 128-dimensional embeddings cluster for different land uses. The interactive 3D UMAP below projects TESSERA embeddings for over 210k hexagonal cells from England's [CROME 2024](https://www.data.gov.uk/dataset/be5d88c9-acfb-4052-bf6b-ee9a416cfe60/crop-map-of-england-crome-2024) crop map into three dimensions. Each point is coloured by its "crop class". Click on the fullscreen button below (top right) and click any point to jump to its location on the satellite map.

Crops with similar seasonal growth patterns (e.g. winter wheat and winter barley) form tight, nearby clusters, demonstrating that the model has learned to capture fine-grained phenological variation purely from self-supervised training on the raw spectral-temporal signal.

