## But inference is the really hard part

The model training happens once, but then (unlike a language model) we needed to generate map tiles for every 10m land pixel on Earth (approximately 1.5 trillion pixels/year). The global embeddings for 2024 alone therefore amount to roughly 250TB of storage. But if we can do this once, then we save vast amounts of work for all of the downstream users, since most of the pretraining has already been completed and the use of the map tiles often requires just a CPU (not even a GPU) for simple tasks.

Consider what the pipeline must do for a single tile (a full [walkthrough is available](https://www.tunbury.org/2026/02/25/tessera-pipeline/)): each Sentinel-2 tile covers a 100km2 region at 10m resolution (about 120 million pixels). For every pixel, the pipeline must:

1. **Assemble** the d-pixel to gather the full annual time series of observations (S1+S2) for that 10m location. These must be co-registered and resampled to the same 10m grid.

2. **Download/filter** from the Sentinel archives (via Microsoft Planetary Computer or AWS) and download cloud masks (the Scene Classification Layer) for every S2 pass over the year, identify the most cloud-free dates and then download the spectral bands for those dates. For S1, both ascending (evening) and descending (morning) passes are collected and merged.

3. **Stack** across the year per pixel and select exactly 40 S1 and S2 timesteps or where fewer than 40 clean observations exist, sample with replacement. The result is a d-pixel shaped `[40, 11]` for Sentinel-2 (10 bands + day-of-year) and `[40, 3]` for Sentinel-1 (VV + VH + day-of-year), with values normalised using global statistics.

4. **Inference** on the d-pixel using only the 46M-parameter encoder, to the compact 128-dimensional output (the false colour tile above visualises this).

5. **Quantize** the embedding to int8 using our quantization-aware training pipeline, producing 128 int8s and a float32 scale factor per pixel. This is a very large compression factor over the raw input and makes global storage feasible.

This pipeline means the bottleneck isn't just GPU compute, but also the network and storage bandwidth. Every tile requires downloading and processing gigabytes of raw satellite imagery before a single forward pass!

## Scaling inference with Vultr and AMD MI325X

For the global inference runs, we initially used the Cambridge [Dawn cluster](https://www.hpc.cam.ac.uk/d-w-n), which generated 100-300 GB of tiles per day, depending on external load factors. We soon switched over to use six Vultr bare-metal nodes, each equipped with eight AMD Instinct MI325X GPUs and AMD EPYC CPUs. That's around 12 terabytes of VRAM across the 48 GPUs, and we continued to use ROCm with PyTorch.

With this setup, we produced roughly **3 TB of compressed embeddings per day**:  equivalent to covering the landmass of Italy every day! The global land surface for a single year takes several months of continuous processing, and so we setup the [dynamic coverage map](/coverage) to let our users monitor the progress of their favourite regions.

The pipeline is structured so that the EPYC CPU cores handle the data assembly by querying STAC catalogues, downloading Sentinel COGs, reprojecting and resampling, and building d-pixel matrices. Then the MI325X GPUs run the encoder inference with the assembled data. We ended up getting rate throttled on downloading satellite data from our primary sources, and so had to set up some temporary VMs on Azure to do some batching there (kindly sponsored by [Tarides](https://tarides.com)).

In summary, the data preparation is I/O-heavy and really benefitted from the high core counts and memory bandwidth of the EPYC platform (we regularly saw load averages of 200+ on each host), while the GPU inference benefits from the large HBM3e capacity that allows generous batch sizes so we weren't constantly just shuffling data around from the CPU to the GPU.

## An OCaml inference alternative

In parallel, we have been developing an [OCaml implementation of the inference pipeline](https://www.tunbury.org/2026/02/15/ocaml-tessera/), replacing the Python stack with native OCaml bindings to ONNX Runtime. Early benchmarks on the same hardware (AMD EPYC 9965, NVIDIA L4) show that an OCaml + ONNX Runtime + CUDA path is the fastest configuration tested (about 20% faster than Python + PyTorch + CUDA on the same dataset), likely due to less data marshalling overhead. The OCaml pipeline produces embedding results that are effectively identical to the Python version, differing only in floating-point rounding at quantization boundaries (well within margins of error).

The OCaml pipeline replaces Python's numpy, rasterio, pystac-client, and stackstac with native OCaml libraries: [ocaml-npy](https://github.com/mtelvers/ocaml-npy) for array I/O, [stac-client](https://github.com/mtelvers/stac-client) for STAC catalogue queries with Planetary Computer SAS token signing, [ocaml-tiff](https://github.com/geocaml/ocaml-tiff) for GeoTIFF reading, and extended [ocaml-gdal](https://github.com/geocaml/ocaml-gdal) bindings for reprojection and remote COG access. Model inference uses [ocaml-onnxruntime](https://github.com/mtelvers/ocaml-onnxruntime) bindings with a thin C shim to ONNX Runtime's C API. This is all very experimental, but we're enjoying optimising the inference stack end to end all the way to the fast GPUs.

## What's next

We used the Vultr machines to generate embeddings for all of Europe from 2017 to 2025, and have almost completed the whole of the USA as well (our two most requested regions from users).  After that we're focusing on Indian region embeddings for the full range.  As we complete each year, the embeddings are published through the [geotessera](https://pypi.org/project/geotessera/) library and are free to use under CC0 for any purpose.

We're really grateful to AMD and Vultr for the hardware access that made the inference on TESSERA v1 possible. In particular, thanks to Joseph Cowell, Rowan Pavlovic, and Kieran Mansley at AMD for their technical support. Thanks especially to Kasia Hilborne and Duncan Ng at Vultr not only for the MI325X bare-metal infrastructure sponsorship, but also their enthusiasm for the project and our environmental goals!

